# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: secure-enclave-usage
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The **Apple A11 Bionic** is a 64-bit ARM-based system on a chip (SoC) designed by Apple Inc., part of the Apple silicon series, and manufactured by TSMC.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] It was only used in the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus, and iPhone X which were introduced on September 12, 2017.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] Apple states that the two high-performance cores are 25% faster than the Apple A10's and the four high-efficiency cores are up to 70% faster than the two corresponding cores in the A10.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The A11 Bionic chip was discontinued on April 15, 2020, following the discontinuation of the iPhone 8 and 8 Plus.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The latest software update for the iPhone 8 & 8 Plus and iPhone X using this chip was iOS 16.7.15, released on March 11th, 2026.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The A11 features an Apple-designed 64-bit ARMv8-A six-core CPU, with two high-performance cores at 2.39 GHz, called **Monsoon**, and four energy-efficient cores, called **Mistral**.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The Monsoon cores are a 7-wide decode out-of-order superscalar design, while the Mistral cores are a 3-wide decode out-of-order superscalar design.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The Mistral cores are based on Apple's Swift cores from the Apple A6.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The A11 uses a new second-generation performance controller, which permits the A11 to use all six cores simultaneously, unlike its predecessor the A10.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The A11 also integrates an Apple-designed three-core graphics processing unit (GPU) with 30% faster graphics performance than the A10.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] Embedded in the A11 is the M11 motion coprocessor.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The A11 includes a new image processor which supports computational photography functions such as lighting estimation, wide color capture, and advanced pixel processing.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The A11 is manufactured by TSMC using a 10 nm FinFET process and contains 4.3 billion transistors on a die 87.66 mm2 in size, 30% smaller than the A10.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] It is manufactured in a package on package (PoP) together with 2 GB of LPDDR4X memory in the iPhone 8 and 3 GB of LPDDR4X memory in the iPhone 8 Plus and iPhone X.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The A11 has video codec encoding support for HEVC and H.264.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] It has decoding support for HEVC, H.264, MPEG‑4 Part 2, and Motion JPEG.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The A11 also includes dedicated neural network hardware that Apple calls a "Neural Engine".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] This neural network hardware can perform up to 600 billion operations per second and is used for Face ID, Animoji and other machine learning tasks.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The neural engine allows Apple to implement neural network and machine learning in a more energy-efficient manner than using either the main CPU or the GPU.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] However, third-party apps cannot use the Neural Engine, leading to similar neural network performance to older iPhones.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] Bloomberg says that the neural engine is the fruit of Apple's efforts to improve its AI team, since the 2015 report by Bloomberg states that Apple's secretive nature made it difficult to attract AI research scientists.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] Apple has since recruited people and multiple companies working on AI, and has published papers related to AI research.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] In October 2016, Apple hired Russ Salakhutdinov as its director of AI research.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/apple-a11] The Apple A11 Bionic chip is used in the following iPhone models and not on any generation of iPad, iPod touch, or Apple TV.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Biometric identifiers are the distinctive, measurable characteristics used to label and describe individuals.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Biometric identifiers are often categorized as physiological characteristics which are related to the shape of the body.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Examples include, but are not limited to fingerprint, palm veins, face recognition, DNA, palm print, hand geometry, iris recognition, retina, odor/scent, voice and shape of ears.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Behavioral characteristics are related to the pattern of behavior of a person, including but not limited to mouse movement, typing rhythm, gait, signature, voice, and behavioral profiling.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Some researchers have coined the term "**Behaviometrics"** (behavioral biometrics) to describe the latter class of biometrics.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] More traditional means of access control include token-based identification systems, such as a driver's license or passport, and knowledge-based identification systems, such as a password or personal identification number.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Since biometric identifiers are unique to individuals, they are more reliable in verifying identity than token and knowledge-based methods; however, the collection of biometric identifiers raises privacy concerns.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Many different aspects of human physiology, chemistry or behavior can be used for biometric authentication.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The selection of a particular biometric for use in a specific application involves a weighting of several factors.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Jain *et al.* (1999) identified seven such factors to be used when assessing the suitability of any trait for use in biometric authentication.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Biometric authentication is based upon biometric recognition which is an advanced method of recognizing biological and behavioral characteristics of an Individual.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Proper biometric use is very application dependent.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Certain biometrics will be better than others based on the required levels of convenience and security.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] No single biometric will meet all the requirements of every possible application.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The block diagram illustrates the two basic modes of a biometric system.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] First, in verification (or authentication) mode the system performs a one-to-one comparison of a captured biometric with a specific template stored in a biometric database in order to verify the individual is the person they claim to be.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Three steps are involved in the verification of a person.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In the first step, reference models for all the users are generated and stored in the model database .
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In the second step, some samples are matched with reference models to generate the genuine and impostor scores and calculate the threshold.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] This process may use a smart card, username, or ID number (e.g.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] PIN) to indicate which template should be used for comparison.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] *Positive recognition* is a common use of the verification mode, "where the aim is to prevent multiple people from using the same identity".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Second, in identification mode the system performs a one-to-many comparison against a biometric database in an attempt to establish the identity of an unknown individual.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The system will succeed in identifying the individual if the comparison of the biometric sample to a template in the database falls within a previously set threshold.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The latter function can only be achieved through biometrics since other methods of personal recognition, such as passwords, PINs, or keys, are ineffective.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The first time an individual uses a biometric system is called *enrollment*.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] During enrollment, biometric information from an individual is captured and stored.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In subsequent uses, biometric information is detected and compared with the information stored at the time of enrollment.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Note that it is crucial that storage and retrieval of such systems themselves be secure if the biometric system is to be robust.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The first block (sensor) is the interface between the real world and the system; it has to acquire all the necessary data.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Most of the time it is an image acquisition system, but it can change according to the characteristics desired.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The second block performs all the necessary pre-processing: it has to remove artifacts from the sensor, to enhance the input (e.g. removing background noise), to use some kind of normalization, etc.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In the third block, necessary features are extracted.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] This step is an important step as the correct features need to be extracted in an optimal way.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] A vector of numbers or an image with particular properties is used to create a *template*.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] A template is a synthesis of the relevant characteristics extracted from the source.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Elements of the biometric measurement that are not used in the comparison algorithm are discarded in the template to reduce the file size and to protect the identity of the enrollee.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] However, depending on the scope of the biometric system, original biometric image sources may be retained, such as the PIV-cards used in the Federal Information Processing Standard Personal Identity Verification (PIV) of Federal Employees and Contractors (FIPS 201).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] During the enrollment phase, the template is simply stored somewhere (on a card or within a database or both).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] During the matching phase, the obtained template is passed to a matcher that compares it with other existing templates, estimating the distance between them using any algorithm (e.g.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The matching program will analyze the template with the input.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] This will then be output for a specified use or purpose (e.g. entrance in a restricted area), though it is a fear that the use of biometric data may face mission creep.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Selection of biometrics in any practical application depending upon the characteristic measurements and user requirements.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In selecting a particular biometric, factors to consider include, performance, social acceptability, ease of circumvention and/or spoofing, robustness, population coverage, size of equipment needed and identity theft deterrence.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The selection of a biometric is based on user requirements and considers sensor and device availability, computational time and reliability, cost, sensor size, and power consumption.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Multimodal biometric systems use multiple sensors or biometrics to overcome the limitations of unimodal biometric systems.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] For instance iris recognition systems can be compromised by aging irises and electronic fingerprint recognition can be worsened by worn-out or cut fingerprints.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] While unimodal biometric systems are limited by the integrity of their identifier, it is unlikely that several unimodal systems will suffer from identical limitations.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Multimodal biometric systems can obtain sets of information from the same marker (i.e., multiple images of an iris, or scans of the same finger) or information from different biometrics (requiring fingerprint scans and, using voice recognition, a spoken passcode).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Multimodal biometric systems can fuse these unimodal systems sequentially, simultaneously, a combination thereof, or in series, which refer to sequential, parallel, hierarchical and serial integration modes, respectively.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Fusion of the biometrics information can occur at different stages of a recognition system.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In case of feature level fusion, the data itself or the features extracted from multiple biometrics are fused.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Matching-score level fusion consolidates the scores generated by multiple classifiers pertaining to different modalities.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Finally, in case of decision level fusion the final results of multiple classifiers are combined via techniques such as majority voting.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Feature level fusion is believed to be more effective than the other levels of fusion because the feature set contains richer information about the input biometric data than the matching score or the output decision of a classifier.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Therefore, fusion at the feature level is expected to provide better recognition results.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Spoof attacks consist in submitting fake biometric traits to biometric systems, and are a major threat that can curtail their security.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Multi-modal biometric systems are commonly believed to be intrinsically more robust to spoof attacks, but recent studies have shown that they can be evaded by spoofing even a single biometric trait.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The Fingerprint Involves minutiae extraction (terminations and bifurcations) and matching techniques.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Steps include image enhancement, binarization, ROI extraction, and minutiae thinning.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The Face system uses class-based scatter matrices to calculate features for recognition, and the Palm Vein acts as an unbreakable cryptographic key, ensuring only the correct user can access the system.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The cancelable Biometrics concept allows biometric traits to be altered slightly to ensure privacy and avoid theft.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] If compromised, new variations of biometric data can be issued.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The Encryption fingerprint template is encrypted using the palm vein key via XOR operations.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] This encrypted Fingerprint is hidden within the face image using steganographic techniques.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Enrollment and Verification for the Biometric data (Fingerprint, palm vein, face) are captured, encrypted, and embedded into a face image.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The system extracts the biometric data and compares it with stored values for Verification.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The system was tested with fingerprint databases, achieving 75% verification accuracy at an equal error rate of 25% and processing time approximately 50 seconds for enrollment and 22 seconds for Verification.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] High security due to palm vein encryption, effective against biometric spoofing, and the multimodal approach ensures reliability if one biometric fails.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Potential for integration with smart cards or on-card systems, enhancing security in personal identification systems.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The discriminating powers of all biometric technologies depend on the amount of entropy they are able to encode and use in matching.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] An early cataloguing of fingerprints dates back to 1885 when Juan Vucetich started a collection of fingerprints of criminals in Argentina.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Josh Ellenbogen and Nitzan Lebovic argued that Biometrics originated in the identification systems of criminal activity developed by Alphonse Bertillon (1853–1914) and by Francis Galton's theory of fingerprints and physiognomy.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Historian Keith Breckenridge note that Galton's travels in South Africa reinforced his early racial prejudices and inspired his later commitment to classifying human difference scientifically.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] According to Lebovic, Galton's work "led to the application of mathematical models to fingerprints, phrenology, and facial characteristics", as part of "absolute identification" and "a key to both inclusion and exclusion" of populations.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Accordingly, "the biometric system is the absolute political weapon of our era" and a form of "soft control".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The theoretician David Lyon showed that during the past two decades biometric systems have penetrated the civilian market, and blurred the lines between governmental forms of control and private corporate control.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Adaptive biometric systems aim to auto-update the templates or model to the intra-class variation of the operational data.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The two-fold advantages of these systems are solving the problem of limited training data and tracking the temporal variations of the input data through adaptation.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Recently, adaptive biometrics have received a significant attention from the research community.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] This research direction is expected to gain momentum because of their key promulgated advantages.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] First, with an adaptive biometric system, one no longer needs to collect a large number of biometric samples during the enrollment process.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Second, it is no longer necessary to enroll again or retrain the system from scratch in order to cope with the changing environment.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] This convenience can significantly reduce the cost of maintaining a biometric system.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Despite these advantages, there are several open issues involved with these systems.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] For mis-classification error (false acceptance) by the biometric system, cause adaptation using impostor sample.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] However, continuous research efforts are directed to resolve the open issues associated to the field of adaptive biometrics.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In recent times, biometrics based on brain (electroencephalogram) and heart (electrocardiogram) signals have emerged.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] An example is finger vein recognition, using pattern-recognition techniques, based on images of human vascular patterns.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The advantage of this newer technology is that it is more fraud resistant compared to conventional biometrics like fingerprints.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] However, such technology is generally more cumbersome and still has issues such as lower accuracy and poor reproducibility over time.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] On the portability side of biometric products, more and more vendors are embracing significantly miniaturized biometric authentication systems (BAS) thereby driving elaborate cost savings, especially for large-scale deployments.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] An operator signature is a biometric mode where the manner in which a person using a device or complex system is recorded as a verification template.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] One potential use for this type of biometric signature is to distinguish among remote users of telerobotic surgery systems that utilize public networks for communication.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] John Michael (Mike) McConnell, a former vice admiral in the United States Navy, a former director of U.S.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] National Intelligence, and senior vice president of Booz Allen Hamilton, promoted the development of a future capability to require biometric authentication to access certain public networks in his keynote speech at the 2009 Biometric Consortium Conference.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] A basic premise in the above proposal is that the person that has uniquely authenticated themselves using biometrics with the computer is in fact also the agent performing potentially malicious actions from that computer.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] However, if control of the computer has been subverted, for example in which the computer is part of a botnet controlled by a hacker, then knowledge of the identity of the user at the terminal does not materially improve network security or aid law enforcement activities.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Rather than tags or tattoos, biometric techniques may be used to identify individual animals: zebra stripes, blood vessel patterns in rodent ears, muzzle prints, bat wing patterns, primate facial recognition and koala spots have all been tried.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Biometrics have been considered also instrumental to the development of state authority (to put it in Foucauldian terms, of discipline and biopower).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] By turning the human subject into a collection of biometric parameters, biometrics would dehumanize the person, infringe bodily integrity, and, ultimately, offend human dignity.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In a well-known case, Italian philosopher Giorgio Agamben refused to enter the United States in protest at the United States Visitor and Immigrant Status Indicator (US-VISIT) program's requirement for visitors to be fingerprinted and photographed.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Agamben argued that gathering of biometric data is a form of bio-political tattooing, akin to the tattooing of Jews during the Holocaust.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] According to Agamben, biometrics turn the human persona into a bare body.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Agamben refers to the two words used by Ancient Greeks for indicating "life", *zoe*, which is the life common to animals and humans, just life; and *bios*, which is life in the human context, with meanings and purposes.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Agamben envisages the reduction to bare bodies for the whole humanity.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] For him, a new bio-political relationship between citizens and the state is turning citizens into pure biological life (*zoe*) depriving them from their humanity (*bios*); and biometrics would herald this new world.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The stark expansion of biometric technologies in both the public and private sector magnifies this concern.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The increasing commodification of biometrics by the private sector adds to this danger of loss of human value.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Indeed, corporations value the biometric characteristics more than the individuals value them.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Other scholars have emphasized, however, that the globalized world is confronted with a huge mass of people with weak or absent civil identities.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Most developing countries have weak and unreliable documents and the poorer people in these countries do not have even those unreliable documents.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Without certified personal identities, there is no certainty of right, no civil liberty.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] One can claim his rights, including the right to refuse to be identified, only if he is an identifiable subject, if he has a public identity.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In such a sense, biometrics could play a pivotal role in supporting and promoting respect for human dignity and fundamental rights.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] It is possible that data obtained during biometric enrollment may be used in ways for which the enrolled individual has not consented.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Moreover, second generation biometrics, notably behavioral and electro-physiologic biometrics (e.g., based on electrocardiography, electroencephalography, electromyography), could be also used for emotion detection.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Unintended application scope: The authentication process correctly identifies the subject when the subject did not wish to be identified.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Covert identification: The subject is identified without seeking identification or authentication, i.e. a subject's face is identified in a crowd.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In terms of recognition or identification performance for a given trait, a biometric system should not exhibit accuracy differences across demographic groups.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Disparities in accuracy can lead to uneven error rates for populations defined by gender, race, age, or other attributes .
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Therefore, biometric systems should be designed and evaluated to ensure demographic fairness, providing equitable performance for all users.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] When thieves cannot get access to secure properties, there is a chance that the thieves will stalk and assault the property owner to gain access.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] If the item is secured with a biometric device, the damage to the owner could be irreversible, and potentially cost more than the secured property.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] For example, in 2005, Malaysian car thieves cut off a man's finger when attempting to steal his Mercedes-Benz S-Class.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In the context of biometric systems, presentation attacks may also be called "spoofing attacks".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] As per the recent ISO/IEC 30107 standard, presentation attacks are defined as "presentation to the biometric capture subsystem with the goal of interfering with the operation of the biometric system".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] These attacks can be either impersonation or obfuscation attacks.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Impersonation attacks try to gain access by pretending to be someone else.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Obfuscation attacks may, for example, try to evade face detection and face recognition systems.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Several methods have been proposed to counteract presentation attacks.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Biometrics are employed by many aid programs in times of crisis in order to prevent fraud and ensure that resources are properly available to those in need.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Humanitarian efforts are motivated by promoting the welfare of individuals in need, however the use of biometrics as a form of surveillance humanitarianism can create conflict due to varying interests of the groups involved in the particular situation.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Disputes over the use of biometrics between aid programs and party officials stalls the distribution of resources to people that need help the most.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In July 2019, the United Nations World Food Program and Houthi Rebels were involved in a large dispute over the use of biometrics to ensure resources are provided to the hundreds of thousands of civilians in Yemen whose lives are threatened.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The refusal to cooperate with the interests of the United Nations World Food Program resulted in the suspension of food aid to the Yemen population.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The use of biometrics may provide aid programs with valuable information, however its potential solutions may not be best suited for chaotic times of crisis.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Conflicts that are caused by deep-rooted political problems, in which the implementation of biometrics may not provide a long-term solution.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] One advantage of passwords over biometrics is that they can be re-issued.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] If a token or a password is lost or stolen, it can be cancelled and replaced by a newer version.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] This is not naturally available in biometrics.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] If someone's face is compromised from a database, they cannot cancel or reissue it.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] If the electronic biometric identifier is stolen, it is nearly impossible to change a biometric feature.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] This renders the person's biometric feature questionable for future use in authentication, such as the case with the hacking of security-clearance-related background information from the Office of Personnel Management (OPM) in the United States.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Cancelable biometrics is a way in which to incorporate protection and the replacement features into biometrics to create a more secure system.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] "Cancelable biometrics refers to the intentional and systematically repeatable distortion of biometric features in order to protect sensitive user-specific data.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] If a cancelable feature is compromised, the distortion characteristics are changed, and the same biometrics is mapped to a new template, which is used subsequently.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Several methods for generating new exclusive biometrics have been proposed.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The first fingerprint-based cancelable biometric system was designed and developed by Tulyakov *et al.* Essentially, cancelable biometrics perform a distortion of the biometric image or features before matching.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The variability in the distortion parameters provides the cancelable nature of the scheme.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Soft biometrics are understood as **not strict biometrical** recognition practices that are proposed in favour of identity cheaters and stealers.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Traits are physical, behavioral or adhered human characteristics that have been derived from the way human beings normally distinguish their peers (e.g. height, gender, hair color).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] They are used to complement the identity information provided by the primary biometric identifiers.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Although soft biometric characteristics lack the distinctiveness and permanence to recognize an individual uniquely and reliably, and can be easily faked, they provide some evidence about the users identity that could be beneficial.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In other words, despite the fact they are unable to individualize a subject, they are effective in distinguishing between people.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Combinations of personal attributes like gender, race, eye color, height and other visible identification marks can be used to improve the performance of traditional biometric systems.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Most soft biometrics can be easily collected and are actually collected during enrollment.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Two main ethical issues are raised by soft biometrics.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Second, soft biometrics have strong potential for categorizing and profiling people, so risking of supporting processes of stigmatization and exclusion.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Many countries, including the United States, are planning to share biometric data with other nations.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] According to an article written in 2009 by S.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Magnuson in the National Defense Magazine entitled "Defense Department Under Pressure to Share Biometric Data" the United States has bilateral agreements with other nations aimed at sharing biometric data.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Certain members of the civilian community are worried about how biometric data is used but full disclosure may not be forthcoming.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] This also potentially applies to Biometrics.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] It goes on to say that this is a classic feature of intelligence and military operations.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] In short, the goal is to preserve the security of 'sources and methods'.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The frequent use of biometric authentication for security and the permanence of an individuals biometrics make the security of biometric data crucial.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The United States does not have a nationwide data privacy law that includes biometrics.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Several states and local governments, led by the Illinois Biometric Information Privacy Act, have legislation regarding biometric data.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The FTC has also taken actions to protect biometric data including against Facebook in 2019, charging they misrepresented their uses of facial recognition technology.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] Among low to middle income countries, roughly 1.2 billion people have already received identification through a biometric identification program.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] There are also numerous countries applying biometrics for voter registration and similar electoral purposes.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] India's national ID program called Aadhaar is the largest biometric database in the world.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] It is a biometrics-based digital identity assigned for a person's lifetime, verifiable online instantly in the public domain, at any time, from anywhere, in a paperless way.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] It is designed to enable government agencies to deliver a retail public service, securely based on biometric data (fingerprint, iris scan and face photo), along with demographic data (name, age, gender, address, parent/spouse name, mobile phone number) of a person.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] The data is transmitted in encrypted form over the internet for authentication, aiming to free it from the limitations of physical presence of a person at a given place.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] About 550 million residents have been enrolled and assigned 480 million Aadhaar national identification numbers as of 7 November 2013.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] It aims to cover the entire population of 1.2 billion in a few years.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] However, it is being challenged by critics over privacy concerns and possible transformation of the state into a surveillance state, or into a Banana republic.§ The project was also met with mistrust regarding the safety of the social protection infrastructures.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] To tackle the fear amongst the people, India's supreme court put a new ruling into action that stated that privacy from then on was seen as a fundamental right.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/biometrics] On 24 August 2017 this new law was established.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] As of December 2023, Apple's App Store contains more than 3.8 million iOS mobile apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Like macOS, it includes components of the Mach microkernel and FreeBSD.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Although some parts of iOS are open source under the Apple Public Source License and other licenses, iOS is proprietary software.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In 2005, when Steve Jobs began planning the iPhone, he stated that he had a choice to either "shrink the Mac, which would be an epic feat of engineering, or enlarge the iPod".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Jobs favored the former approach but pitted the Macintosh and iPod teams, led by Scott Forstall and Tony Fadell, respectively, against each other in an internal competition, with Forstall winning by creating iPhone OS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The decision enabled the success of the iPhone as a platform for third-party developers: using a well-known desktop operating system as its basis allowed the many third-party Mac developers to write software for the iPhone with minimal retraining.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Forstall was also responsible for creating a software development kit for programmers to build iPhone apps, as well as an App Store within iTunes.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The operating system was unveiled with the iPhone at the Macworld Conference & Expo on January 9, 2007, and released in June of that year.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] At the time of its unveiling in January, Steve Jobs claimed: "iPhone runs OS X" and runs "desktop class applications", but at the time of the iPhone's release, the operating system was renamed "iPhone OS".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Initially, third-party native applications were not supported.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Jobs' reasoning was that developers could build web applications through the Safari web browser that "would behave like native apps on the iPhone".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In October 2007, Apple announced that a native software development kit (SDK) was under development and that they planned to put it "in developers' hands in February".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] On March 6, 2008, Apple held a press event, announcing the iPhone SDK.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The iOS App Store was opened on July 10, 2008, with an initial 500 applications available.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] As of March 2016, 1 million apps are natively compatible with the iPad tablet computer.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] These apps have collectively been downloaded more than 130 billion times.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] App intelligence firm Sensor Tower estimated that the App Store would reach 5 million apps by 2020.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In September 2007, Apple announced the iPod Touch, a redesigned iPod based on the iPhone form factor.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It also includes a mobile version of Safari for web browsing, as well as access to the App Store, iTunes Library, iBookstore, Contacts, and Notes.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Content is downloadable via Wi-Fi and optional 3G service or synced through the user's computer.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] AT&T was initially the sole U.S. provider of 3G wireless access for the iPad.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In June 2010, Apple rebranded iPhone OS as "iOS".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The trademark "IOS" had been used by Cisco for over a decade for its operating system, IOS, used on its routers.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] To avoid any potential lawsuit, Apple licensed the "IOS" trademark from Cisco.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The Apple Watch smartwatch was announced by Tim Cook on September 9, 2014, being introduced as a product with health and fitness-tracking.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It uses watchOS as its operating system; watchOS is based on iOS, with new features created specially for the Apple Watch such as an activity tracking app.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In October 2016, Apple opened its first iOS Developer Academy in Naples inside University of Naples Federico II's new campus.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The course is completely free, aimed at acquiring specific technical skills on the creation and management of applications for the Apple ecosystem platforms.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] At the academy there are also issues of business administration (business planning and business management with a focus on digital opportunities) and there is a path dedicated to the design of graphical interfaces.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Students have the opportunity to participate in the "Enterprise Track", an in-depth training experience on the entire life cycle of an app, from design to implementation, to security, troubleshooting, data storage and cloud usage.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] As of 2020, the academy graduated almost a thousand students from all over the world, who have worked on 400 app ideas and have already published about 50 apps on the iOS App Store.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In the 2018–2019 academic year, students from more than 30 countries arrived.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] 35 of these have been selected to attend the Worldwide Developer Conference, the annual Apple Developer Conference held annually in California in early June.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] On June 3, 2019, iPadOS, the branded version of iOS for iPad, was announced during the WWDC 2019 keynote; it was launched on September 25, 2019.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] On June 9, 2025, at WWDC 2025, Apple introduced iOS 26.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The version number indicates the year following the year in which the version was introduced; this numbering scheme is now being used for all Apple operating systems, keeping their version numbers synchronized.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] On June 8, 2026, at WWDC 2026, Apple introduced iOS 27.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It introduces Siri AI, a new model designed by Apple in collaboration with Google.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Siri AI is able to handle significantly more complex tasks, such as making shortcuts in the Shortcuts app and planning advanced routes.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The revamped Siri is similar to an AI chatbot, and it will receive an app where users can look at their past conversations.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The iOS user interface is based upon direct manipulation, using multi-touch gestures such as *swipe*, *tap*, *pinch*, and *reverse pinch*.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Interface control elements include sliders, switches, and buttons.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Internal accelerometers are used by some applications to respond to shaking the device (one common result is the undo command) or rotating it in three dimensions (one common result is switching between portrait and landscape mode).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Various accessibility described in § Accessibility functions enable users with vision and hearing disabilities to properly use iOS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The lock screen shows the time and a user's lock screen widgets, which display timely information from apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The lock screen also has two buttons, called Controls, which are only available on iPhone.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] These default to flashlight and camera, but they can be customized to any control available in Control Center and can also be removed.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Along the top of the screen is a status bar, showing information about the device and its connectivity.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It is possible to manage brightness, volume, wireless connections, music player, etc.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Scrolling from the top left to the bottom (or top to bottom on iPhones with Touch ID) will open the Notification Center, which in the latest versions of iOS is very similar to the lock screen.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It displays notifications in chronological order and groups them by application.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] From the notifications of some apps it is possible to interact directly, for example by replying to a message directly from it.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Both can be found in the Notification Center, and show for a set amount of time on the lock screen (unless the user has Notification Center allowed when locked).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] On iPhones with Touch ID, screenshots can be created with the simultaneous press of the home and power buttons.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In comparison to Android, which requires the buttons to be held down, a short press does suffice on iOS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] On iPhone with Face ID, screenshots are captured using the volume-up and power buttons instead.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The camera application used a skeuomorphic closing camera shutter animation prior to iOS 7.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Since then, it uses a simple short blackout effect.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Some camera settings such as video resolution and frame rate are not adjustable through the camera interface itself, but are outsourced to the system settings.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] A new feature in iOS 13 called "context menus" shows related actions when you touch and hold an item.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] When the context menu is displayed, the background is blurred.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] To choose from a few options, a selection control is used.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Selectors can appear anchored at the bottom or in line with the content (called date selectors).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Date selectors take on the appearance of any other selection control, but with a column for day, month, and optionally year.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Alerts appear in the center of the screen, but there are also alerts that scroll up from the bottom of the screen (called "action panels").
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Destructive actions (such as eliminating any element) are colored red.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The official font of iOS is San Francisco.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It is designed for small text readability, and is used throughout the operating system, including third-party apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The icons are 180x180px in size for iPhones with a larger screen, usually models over 6 inches, including iPhone 11 Pro and iPhone 8 Plus, while they are 120x120px on iPhones with smaller displays.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The home screen appears whenever the user unlocks the device, presses the physical "Home" button while in an app, or swipes up from the bottom of the screen using the home bar.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The screen has a status bar across the top to display data, such as time, battery level, and signal strength.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The rest of the screen is devoted to the current application.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] When a passcode is set and a user switches on the device, the passcode must be entered at the Lock Screen before access to the Home screen is granted.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iPhone OS 3, Spotlight was introduced, allowing users to search media, apps, emails, contacts, messages, reminders, calendar events, and similar content.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 7 and later, Spotlight is accessed by pulling down anywhere on the home screen (except for the top and bottom edges that open Notification Center and Control Center).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 9, there are two ways to access Spotlight.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] As with iOS 7 and 8, pulling down on any homescreen will show Spotlight.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] However, it can also be accessed as it was in iOS versions 3 through 6.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] This endows Spotlight with Siri suggestions, which include app suggestions, contact suggestions and news.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 10, Spotlight is at the top of the now-dedicated "Today" panel.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] With the release of iPhone OS 3.2, users gained the ability to set a wallpaper for the Home Screen.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS 7 introduced a parallax effect on the Home Screen, which shifts the device's wallpaper and icons in response to the movement of the device, creating a 3D effect and an illusion of floating icons.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] This effect is also visible in the tab view of Mail and Safari.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Researchers found that users organize icons on their homescreens based on usage frequency and relatedness of the applications, as well as for reasons of usability and aesthetics.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS originally used Helvetica as the system font.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Apple switched to Helvetica Neue exclusively for the iPhone 4 and its Retina Display, and retained Helvetica as the system font for older iPhone devices on iOS 4.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] With iOS 7, Apple announced that they would change the system font to Helvetica Neue Light, a decision that sparked criticism for inappropriate usage of a light, thin typeface for low-resolution mobile screens.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Apple eventually chose Helvetica Neue instead.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The release of iOS 7 also introduced the ability to scale text or apply other forms of text accessibility changes through Settings.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] With iOS 9, Apple changed the font to San Francisco, an Apple-designed font aimed at maximum legibility and font consistency across its product lineup.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS 4 introduced folders, which can be created by dragging an application on top of another, and from then on, more items can be added to the folder using the same procedure.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] A title for the folder is automatically selected by the category of applications inside, but the name can also be edited by the user.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] When apps inside folders receive notification badges, the individual numbers of notifications are added up and the total number is displayed as a notification badge on the folder itself.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Originally, folders on an iPhone could include up to 12 apps, while folders on iPad could include 20.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] With increasing display sizes on newer iPhone hardware, iOS 7 updated the folders with pages similar to the home screen layout, allowing for a significant expansion of folder functionality.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Each page of a folder can contain up to nine apps, and there can be 15 pages in total, allowing for a total of 135 apps in a single folder.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 9, Apple updated folder sizes for iPad hardware, allowing for 16 apps per page, still at 15 pages maximum, increasing the total to 240 apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Before iOS 5, notifications were delivered in a modal window and could not be viewed after being dismissed.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 5, Apple introduced Notification Center, which allows users to view a history of notifications.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The user can tap a notification to open its corresponding app, or clear it.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Notifications are now delivered in banners that appear briefly at the top of the screen.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] If a user taps a received notification, the application that sent the notification will be opened.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Users can also choose to view notifications in modal alert windows by adjusting the application's notification settings.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Introduced with iOS 8, widgets are now accessible through the Notification Center, defined by 3rd parties.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] When an app sends a notification while closed, a red badge appears on its icon.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] This badge tells the user, at a glance, how many notifications that app has sent.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS devices come with preinstalled apps developed by Apple including Mail, Maps, TV, Music, FaceTime, Wallet, Health, and many more.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Applications ("apps") are the most general form of application software that can be installed on iOS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] They are downloaded from the official catalog of the App Store digital store, where apps are subjected to security checks before being made available to users.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In June 2017, Apple updated its guidelines to specify that app developers will no longer have the ability to use custom prompts for encouraging users to leave reviews for their apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] IOS applications can also be installed directly from an IPA file provided by the software distributor, via unofficial ways.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] They are written using iOS Software Development Kit (SDK) and, often, combined with Xcode, using officially supported programming languages, including Swift and Objective-C.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Other companies have also created tools that allow for the development of native iOS apps using their respective programming languages.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Applications for iOS are mostly built using components of UIKit, a programming framework.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It allows applications to have a consistent look and feel with the OS, nevertheless offering customization.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Elements automatically update along with iOS updates, automatically including new interface rules.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] UIKit elements are very adaptable, this allows developers to design a single app that looks the same on any iOS device.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In addition to defining the iOS interface, UIKit defines the functionality of the application.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] At first, Apple did not intend to release an SDK to developers, because they did not want third-party apps to be developed for iOS, building web apps instead.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] However, this technology never entered into common use, this led Apple to change its opinion, so in October 2007 the SDK for developers was announced, finally released on March 6, 2008.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The SDK includes an inclusive set of development tools, including an audio mixer and an iPhone simulator.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It is not available for Microsoft Windows PCs.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] To test the application, get technical support, and distribute applications through App Store, developers are required to subscribe to the Apple Developer Program.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Over the years, the Apple Store apps surpassed multiple major milestones, including 50,000, 100,000, 250,000, 500,000, 1 million, and 2 million apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The billionth application was installed on April 24, 2009.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] App Library automatically categorizes apps into folders based on their function or type and includes an alphabetical list of all installed apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] For example, it might group all social media apps into one folder and productivity apps into another.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Users can quickly find and access apps by using the search bar at the top of the App Library.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Users can choose to hide specific app pages from the home screen, making it easier to focus on the apps they use most frequently.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS enforces strict sandboxing to maintain security and privacy.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Apps are generally limited to accessing their own containers and specific system-provided directories, such as the Photos library.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] To access files outside of their sandbox, iOS uses mechanisms like document pickers, file providers, and app extensions.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS 8 introduced the Document Picker and Document Provider extensions as part of the document interaction controller.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] This allows apps to open, save, and interact with documents stored in a central location or cloud storage services.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] With iOS 11, Apple introduced the Files app and the File Provider extension, providing a central location for users to manage and organize their files.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Apps can integrate with the Files app to make their documents accessible and editable directly from the Files app.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] These files can be accessed across multiple devices as long as the user is signed in with the same Apple ID.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS offers various accessibility features to help users with vision and hearing disabilities.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] One major feature, VoiceOver, provides a voice reading information on the screen, including contextual buttons, icons, links and other user interface elements, and allows the user to navigate the operating system through gestures.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Any apps with default controls and developed with a UIKit framework gets VoiceOver functionality built in.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] One example includes holding up the iPhone to take a photo, with VoiceOver describing the photo scenery.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] As part of a "Made for iPhone" program, introduced with the release of iOS 7 in 2013, Apple has developed technology to use Bluetooth and a special technology protocol to let compatible third-party equipment connect with iPhones and iPads for streaming audio directly to a user's ears.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Additional customization available for Made for iPhone products include battery tracking and adjustable sound settings for different environments.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Building into the core of our products supports a vision of an inclusive world where opportunity and access to information are barrier-free, empowering individuals with disabilities to achieve their goals".
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Criticism has been aimed at iOS depending on both internet connection (either WiFi or through iTunes) and a working SIM card upon first activation.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] This restriction has been loosened in iOS 12, which no longer requires the latter.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Multitasking for iOS was first released in June 2010 along with the release of iOS 4.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Only certain devices—iPhone 4, iPhone 3GS, and iPod Touch 3rd generation—were able to multitask.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The iPad did not get multitasking until iOS 4.2.1 in that November.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The implementation of multitasking in iOS has been criticized for its approach, which limits the work that applications in the background can perform to a limited function set and requires application developers to add explicit support for it.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Before iOS 4, multitasking was limited to a selection of the applications Apple included on the device.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Users could however "jailbreak" their device in order to unofficially multitask.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 7, Apple introduced a new multitasking feature, providing all apps with the ability to perform background updates.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] This feature prefers to update the user's most frequently used apps and prefers to use Wi-Fi networks over a cellular network, without markedly reducing the device's battery life.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 4.0 to iOS 6.x, double-clicking the home button activates the application switcher.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] A scrollable dock-style interface appears from the bottom, moving the contents of the screen up.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Choosing an icon switches to an application.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] To the far left are icons which function as music controls, a rotation lock, and on iOS 4.2 and above, a volume controller.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] With the introduction of iOS 7, double-clicking the home button also activates the application switcher.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] However, unlike previous versions it displays screenshots of open applications on top of the icon and horizontal scrolling allows for browsing through previous apps, and it is possible to close applications by dragging them up, similar to how WebOS handled multiple cards.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Now, instead of the home screen appearing at the leftmost of the application switcher, it appears rightmost.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 11, the application switcher receives a major redesign.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In the iPad, the Control Center and app switcher are combined.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The app switcher in the iPad can also be accessed by swiping up from the bottom.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In the iPhone, the app switcher cannot be accessed if there are no apps in the RAM.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 4.0 to iOS 6.x, briefly holding the icons in the application switcher makes them "jiggle" (similarly to the homescreen) and allows the user to *force* quit the applications by tapping the red minus circle that appears at the corner of the app's icon.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Clearing applications from multitasking stayed the same from iOS 4.0 through 6.1.6, the last version of iOS 6.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] As of iOS 7, the process has become faster and easier.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In iOS 7, instead of holding the icons to close them, they are closed by simply swiping them upwards off the screen.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Up to three apps can be cleared at a time compared to one in versions up to iOS 6.1.6.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Task completion allows apps to continue a certain task after the app has been suspended.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] As of iOS 4.0, apps can request up to ten minutes to complete a task in the background.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] This doesn't extend to background uploads and downloads though (e.g. if a user starts a download in one application, it won't finish if they switch away from the application).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Siri (/ˈsɪri/) is a virtual assistant integrated into iOS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The assistant uses voice queries and a natural-language user interface to answer questions, make recommendations, and perform actions by delegating requests to a set of Internet services.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The software adapts to users' individual language usages, searches, and preferences, with continuing use.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Originally released as an app for iOS in February 2010, it was acquired by Apple two months later, and then integrated into iPhone 4S at its release in October 2011.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] At that time, the separate app was also removed from the iOS App Store.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Siri supports a wide range of user commands, including performing phone actions, checking basic information, scheduling events and reminders, handling device settings, searching the Internet, navigating areas, finding information on entertainment, and is able to engage with iOS-integrated apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] With the release of iOS 10 in 2016, Apple opened up limited third-party access to Siri, including third-party messaging apps, as well as payments, ride-sharing, and Internet calling apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Game Center is an online multiplayer "social gaming network" released by Apple.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It allows users to "invite friends to play a game, start a multiplayer game through matchmaking, track their achievements, and compare their high scores on a leaderboard." iOS 5 and above adds support for profile photos.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Game Center was announced during an iOS 4 preview event hosted by Apple on April 8, 2010.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] A preview was released to registered Apple developers in August.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It was released on September 8, 2010, with iOS 4.1 on iPhone 4, iPhone 3GS, and iPod Touch 2nd generation through 4th generation.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Game Center made its public debut on the iPad with iOS 4.2.1.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] There is no support for the iPhone 3G, original iPhone and the first-generation iPod Touch (the latter two devices did not have Game Center because they did not get iOS 4).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] However, Game Center is unofficially available on the iPhone 3G via a hack.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The instruction set architectures supported by iOS are the ARM architectures.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS powers almost exclusively Apple hardware.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It is used for all iPhones and iPod Touch devices.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Further, Apple Watches, Apple TVs, and iPads either also use iOS for some models or use OSes based on iOS for other models.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The iOS software development kit (SDK) allows for the development of mobile apps that can run on iOS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] While originally developing iPhone prior to its unveiling in 2007, Apple's then-CEO Steve Jobs did not intend to let third-party developers build native apps for iOS, instead directing them to make web applications for the Safari web browser.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] However, backlash from developers prompted the company to reconsider, with Jobs announcing in October 2007 that Apple would have a software development kit available for developers by February 2008.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The SDK is a free download for users of Mac personal computers.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The SDK contains sets giving developers access to various functions and services of iOS devices, such as hardware and software attributes.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It also contains an iPhone simulator to mimic the look and feel of the device on the computer while developing.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] New versions of the SDK accompany new versions of iOS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In order to test applications, get technical support, and distribute apps through App Store, developers are required to subscribe to the Apple Developer Program.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Combined with Xcode, the iOS SDK helps developers write iOS apps using officially supported programming languages, including Swift and Objective-C.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Apple provides major updates to the iOS operating system annually.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Since iOS 5, the primary method of delivery has been over-the-air.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Updates are also available using iTunes on older versions of macOS and Windows, using Finder on macOS starting with macOS Catalina, and using the Apple Devices app on Windows starting with Windows 10 version 22H2.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The device checks an XML-based PLIST file on mesu.apple.com for updates.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Updates are delivered as unencrypted ZIP files.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Updates are checked for regularly, and are downloaded and installed automatically if enabled.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Otherwise, the user can install them manually or are prompted to allow automatic installation overnight if plugged in and connected to Wi-Fi.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iPod Touch users originally had to pay for system software updates due to accounting rules that designated it not a "subscription device" like the iPhone or Apple TV, causing many iPod Touch owners not to update.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In September 2009, a change in accounting rules won tentative approval, affecting Apple's earnings and stock price, and allowing iPod Touch updates to be delivered free of charge.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Apple significantly extended the cycle of updates for iOS-supported devices over the years.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The iPhone (1st generation) and iPhone 3G only received two major iOS updates, while later models had support for three to seven major updates.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS uses the XNU kernel included in the Darwin operating system and used by macOS, adapted to work with devices that run iOS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Since its initial release, iOS has been subject to a variety of different hacks centered around adding functionality not allowed by Apple.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Prior to the 2008 debut of Apple's native iOS App Store, the primary motive for jailbreaking was to bypass Apple's purchase mechanism for installing the App Store's native applications.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Apple claimed that it would not release iOS software updates designed specifically to break these tools (other than applications that perform SIM unlocking); however, with each subsequent iOS update, previously un-patched jailbreak exploits are usually patched.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] When a device is booting, it loads Apple's own kernel initially, so a jailbroken device must be exploited and have the kernel patched each time it is booted up.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] An *untethered* jailbreak uses exploits that are powerful enough to allow the user to turn their device off and back on at will, with the device starting up completely, and the kernel will be patched without the help of a computer – in other words, it will be jailbroken even after each reboot.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] A tethered jailbreak is only able to temporarily jailbreak the device during a single boot.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] If the user turns the device off and then boots it back up without the help of a jailbreak tool, the device will no longer be running a patched kernel, and it may get stuck in a partially started state, such as Recovery Mode.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In order for the device to start completely and with a patched kernel, it must be "re-jailbroken" with a computer (using the "boot tethered" feature of a tool) each time it is turned on.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] All changes to the files on the device (such as installed package files or edited system files) will persist between reboots, including changes that can only function if the device is jailbroken (such as installed package files).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In more recent years, two other solutions have been created – *semi-tethered* and *semi-untethered*.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] A semi-tethered solution is one where the device is able to start up on its own, but it will no longer have a patched kernel, and therefore will not be able to run modified code.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] It will, however, still be usable for normal functions, just like stock iOS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] To start with a patched kernel, the user must start the device with the help of the jailbreak tool.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] A semi-untethered jailbreak gives the ability to start the device on its own.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] On first boot, the device will not be running a patched kernel.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] However, rather than having to run a tool from a computer to apply the kernel patches, the user is able to re-jailbreak their device with the help of an app (usually sideloaded using Cydia Impactor) running on their device.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In the case of the iOS 9.2-9.3.3 and 64-bit 10.x jailbreaks, Safari-based exploits were available, thereby meaning websites could be used to re-jailbreak.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In more detail: Each iOS device has a bootchain that tries to make sure only trusted/signed code is loaded.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] A device with a tethered jailbreak is able to boot up with the help of a jailbreaking tool because the tool executes exploits via USB that bypass parts of that "chain of trust", bootstrapping to a pwned (no signature check) iBEC, or iBoot to finish the boot process.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Since the arrival of Apple's native iOS App Store, and—along with it—third-party applications, the general motives for jailbreaking have changed.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] People jailbreak for many different reasons, including gaining filesystem access, installing custom device themes, and modifying SpringBoard.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] An additional motivation is that it may enable the installation of pirated apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] On some devices, jailbreaking also makes it possible to install alternative operating systems, such as Android and the Linux kernel.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Primarily, users jailbreak their devices because of the limitations of iOS.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Depending on the method used, the effects of jailbreaking may be permanent or temporary.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In 2010, the Electronic Frontier Foundation (EFF) successfully convinced the U.S.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Copyright Office to allow an exemption to the general prohibition on circumvention of copyright protection systems under the Digital Millennium Copyright Act (DMCA).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The exemption allows jailbreaking of iPhones for the sole purpose of allowing legally obtained applications to be added to the iPhone.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The exemption does not affect the contractual relations between Apple and an iPhone owner, for example, jailbreaking voiding the iPhone warranty; however, it is solely based on Apple's discretion on whether they will fix jailbroken devices in the event that they need to be repaired.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] At the same time, the Copyright Office exempted unlocking an iPhone from DMCA's anticircumvention prohibitions.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Unlocking an iPhone allows the iPhone to be used with any wireless carrier using the same GSM or CDMA technology for which the particular phone model was designed to operate.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Initially most wireless carriers in the US did not allow iPhone owners to unlock it for use with other carriers.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] However AT&T allowed iPhone owners who had satisfied contract requirements to unlock their iPhone.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Instructions to unlock the device are available from Apple, but it is ultimately at the sole discretion of the carrier to authorize unlocking the device.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] This allows the use of a carrier-sourced iPhone on other networks.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Modern versions of iOS and the iPhone fully support LTE across multiple carriers wherever the phone was purchased.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Programs to remove SIM lock restrictions are available, but are not supported by Apple, and most often not a permanent unlock – a soft unlock, which modifies the iPhone so that the baseband will accept the SIM card of any GSM carrier.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] SIM unlocking is not jailbreaking, but a jailbreak is also required for these unofficial software unlocks.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] The legality of software unlocking varies in each country; for example, in the US, there is a DMCA exemption for unofficial software unlocking of devices purchased before January 26, 2013.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Competitor Microsoft, via a PR spokesman, criticized Apple's control over its platform.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Particularly at issue is the ability for Apple to remotely disable or delete apps at will.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Some in the tech community have expressed concern that the locked-down iOS represents a growing trend in Apple's approach to computing, particularly Apple's shift away from machines that hobbyists can "tinker with" and note the potential for such restrictions to stifle software innovation.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Former Facebook developer Joe Hewitt protested against Apple's control over its hardware as a "horrible precedent" but praised iOS's sandboxing of apps.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS utilizes many security features in both hardware and software.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] iOS is the second most popular mobile operating system in the world, after Android.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Sales of iPads in recent years are also behind Android, while, by web use (a proxy for all use), iPads (using iOS) are still the most popular.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] At WWDC 2014, Tim Cook said 800 million devices had been sold by June 2014.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] During Apple's quarterly earnings call in January 2015, the company announced that they had sold over one billion iOS devices since 2007.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] By February 2023, there were 2 billion devices activated, and 1.5 billion iPhones had been sold since 2007.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] By late 2011, iOS accounted for 60% of the market share for smartphones and tablets.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] By the end of 2014, iOS accounted for 14.8% of the smartphone market and 27.6% of the tablet and two-in-one market.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In May 2023, StatCounter reported iOS was used on 31.44% of smartphones and 55.75% of tablets worldwide, measured by internet usage instead of sales.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] In the third quarter of 2015, research from Strategy Analytics showed that iOS adoption of the worldwide smartphone market was at a record low 12.1%, attributed to lackluster performance in China and Africa.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/ios] Android accounted for 87.5% of the market, with Windows Phone and BlackBerry accounting for the rest.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Mobile application development presents certain security challenges that are unique compared to web applications and other forms of software.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] This cheat sheet provides guidance on security considerations for mobile app development.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] It is not a comprehensive guide by any means, but rather a starting point for developers to consider security in their mobile app development.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For more information, see the Secure Product Design Cheat Sheet.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Developing with third-party libraries and components introduces the possibility of security unknowns.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] See the Vulnerable Dependency Management Cheat Sheet for recommendations on managing third-party dependencies when vulnerabilities are discovered.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Authentication is a complex topic and there are many pitfalls.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] Authentication logic must be written and tested with extreme care.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] The tips here are only a starting point and barely scratch the surface.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For more information, see the Authentication Cheat Sheet and M1: Insecure Authentication/Authorization from the OWASP Mobile Top 10.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] See the Logging Cheat Sheet for examples of data that should not be logged.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is assigned to the Action Button (on iPhone 15 Pro and iPhone 16 Pro models), it can be executed by pressing the Action Button while the device is locked.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is assigned to the Control Center (on iOS/iPadOS 18+), it can be executed by pulling up the Control Center and pressing the Shortcut button while the device is locked.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] A Shortcut can be invoked via Siri while the device is locked.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is added to the user's Home Screen (on iOS/iPadOS 18+), it can be directly executed by tapping the Shortcut button on the user's lock screen while the device is locked.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] If a Shortcut is set to run at a specific interval or a specific time, it can execute even if the device is locked.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For further reading, visit the OWASP Mobile Top 10 Project.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/mobile-application-security-cheat-sheet] For a more detailed framework for mobile security, see the OWASP Mobile Application Security Project.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] A **secure cryptoprocessor** is a dedicated computer-on-a-chip or microprocessor for carrying out cryptographic operations, embedded in a packaging with multiple physical security measures, which give it a degree of tamper resistance.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Unlike cryptographic processors that output decrypted data onto a bus in a secure environment, a secure cryptoprocessor does not output decrypted data or decrypted program instructions in an environment where security cannot always be maintained.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] The purpose of a secure cryptoprocessor is to act as the keystone of a security subsystem, eliminating the need to protect the rest of the subsystem with physical security measures.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] A hardware security module (HSM) contains one or more secure cryptoprocessor chips.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] These devices are high grade secure cryptoprocessors used with enterprise servers.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] A hardware security module can have multiple levels of physical security with a single-chip cryptoprocessor as its most secure component.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] The cryptoprocessor does not reveal keys or executable instructions on a bus, except in encrypted form, and zeros keys by attempts at probing or scanning.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] The crypto chip(s) may also be potted in the hardware security module with other processors and memory chips that store and process encrypted data.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Any attempt to remove the potting will cause the keys in the crypto chip to be zeroed.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] A hardware security module may also be part of a computer (for example an ATM) that operates inside a locked safe to deter theft, substitution, and tampering.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Some secure cryptoprocessors can even run general-purpose operating systems such as Linux inside their security boundary.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Cryptoprocessors input program instructions in encrypted form and decrypt the instructions to plain instructions, which are then executed within the same cryptoprocessor chip where the decrypted instructions are inaccessibly stored.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] By never revealing the decrypted program instructions, the cryptoprocessor prevents tampering of programs by technicians who may have legitimate access to the sub-system data bus.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Data processed by a cryptoprocessor is also frequently encrypted.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] The Trusted Platform Module (TPM) is an implementation of a secure cryptoprocessor that brings the notion of trusted computing to ordinary PCs by enabling a secure environment.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Present TPM implementations focus on providing a tamper-proof boot environment, and persistent and volatile storage encryption.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Security chips for embedded systems are also available that provide the same level of physical protection for keys and other secret material as a smartcard processor or TPM but in a smaller, less complex and less expensive package.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] They are often referred to as cryptographic authentication devices and are used to authenticate peripherals, accessories and/or consumables.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Like TPMs, they are usually turnkey integrated circuits intended to be embedded in a system, usually soldered to a PC board.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Secure cryptoprocessors, while useful, are not invulnerable to attack, particularly for well-equipped and determined opponents (e.g. a government intelligence agency) who are willing to expend enough resources on the project.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] One attack on a secure cryptoprocessor targeted the IBM 4758.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] A team at the University of Cambridge reported the successful extraction of secret information from an IBM 4758, using a combination of mathematics, and special-purpose codebreaking hardware.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] However, this attack was not practical in real-world systems because it required the attacker to have full access to all API functions of the device.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Normal and recommended practices use the integral access control system to split authority so that no one person could mount the attack.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Smartcards are significantly more vulnerable, as they are more open to physical attack.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Additionally, hardware backdoors can undermine security in smartcards and other cryptoprocessors unless investment is made in anti-backdoor design methods.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] This would require both physical possession of the device as well as skills and equipment beyond that of most technical personnel.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Other attack methods involve carefully analyzing the timing of various operations that might vary depending on the secret value or mapping the current consumption versus time to identify differences in the way that '0' bits are handled internally vs.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Or the attacker may apply temperature extremes, excessively high or low clock frequencies or supply voltage that exceeds the specifications in order to induce a fault.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] The internal design of the cryptoprocessor can be tailored to prevent these attacks.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] The first single-chip cryptoprocessor design was for copy protection of personal computer software (see US Patent 4,168,396, Sept 18, 1979) and was inspired by Bill Gates's Open Letter to Hobbyists.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] The hardware security module (HSM), a type of secure cryptoprocessor, was invented by Egyptian-American engineer Mohamed M.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] He invented a high security module dubbed the "Atalla Box" which encrypted PIN and ATM messages, and protected offline devices with an un-guessable PIN-generating key.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] In 1972, he filed a patent for the device.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] He founded Atalla Corporation (now Utimaco Atalla) that year, and commercialized the "Atalla Box" the following year, officially as the Identikey system.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] It was a card reader and customer identification system, consisting of a card reader console, two customer PIN pads, intelligent controller and built-in electronic interface package.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] It allowed the customer to type in a secret code, which is transformed by the device, using a microprocessor, into another code for the teller.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] During a transaction, the customer's account number was read by the card reader.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] It was a success, and led to the wide use of high security modules.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Fearful that Atalla would dominate the market, banks and credit card companies began working on an international standard in the 1970s.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] The IBM 3624, launched in the late 1970s, adopted a similar PIN verification process to the earlier Atalla system.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Atalla was an early competitor to IBM in the banking security market.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] At the National Association of Mutual Savings Banks (NAMSB) conference in January 1976, Atalla unveiled an upgrade to its Identikey system, called the Interchange Identikey.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] It added the capabilities of processing online transactions and dealing with network security.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Designed with the focus of taking bank transactions online, the Identikey system was extended to shared-facility operations.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] It was consistent and compatible with various switching networks, and was capable of resetting itself electronically to any one of 64,000 irreversible nonlinear algorithms as directed by card data information.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] The Interchange Identikey device was released in March 1976.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Later in 1979, Atalla introduced the first network security processor (NSP).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/secure-cryptoprocessor] Atalla's HSM products protect 250 million card transactions every day as of 2013, and secure the majority of the world's ATM transactions as of 2014.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] A **trusted execution environment** (**TEE**) is a secure area of a main processor.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] It helps the code and data loaded inside it be protected with respect to confidentiality and integrity.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Data confidentiality prevents unauthorized entities from outside the TEE from reading data, while code integrity prevents code in the TEE from being replaced or modified by unauthorized entities, which may also be the computer owner itself as in certain DRM schemes described in Intel SGX.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] This is done by implementing unique, immutable, and confidential architectural security, which offers hardware-based memory encryption that isolates specific application code and data in memory.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] This allows user-level code to allocate private regions of memory, called enclaves, which are designed to be protected from processes running at higher privilege levels.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE as an isolated execution environment provides security features such as isolated execution, integrity of applications executing with the TEE, and confidentiality of their assets.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] In general terms, the TEE offers an execution space that provides a higher level of security for trusted applications running on the device than a rich operating system (OS) and more functionality than a 'secure element' (SE).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The first security level, Profile 1, was targeted against only software attacks, while Profile 2, was targeted against both software and hardware attacks.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Commercial TEE solutions based on ARM TrustZone technology, conforming to the TR1 standard, were later launched, such as Trusted Foundations developed by Trusted Logic.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Work on the OMTP standards ended in mid-2010 when the group transitioned into the Wholesale Applications Community (WAC).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The OMTP standards, including those defining a TEE, are hosted by GSMA.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE typically consists of a hardware isolation mechanism plus a secure operating system running on top of that isolation mechanism, although the term has been used more generally to mean a protected solution.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Whilst a GlobalPlatform TEE requires hardware isolation, others, such as EMVCo, use the term TEE to refer to both hardware and software-based solutions.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] FIDO uses the concept of TEE in the restricted operating environment for TEEs based on hardware isolation.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Only trusted applications running in a TEE have access to the full power of a device's main processor, peripherals, and memory, while hardware isolation protects these from user-installed apps running in a main operating system.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Software and cryptography inside the TEE protects the trusted applications contained within from each other.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Service providers, mobile network operators (MNO), operating system developers, application developers, device manufacturers, platform providers, and silicon vendors are the main stakeholders contributing to the standardization efforts around the TEE.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] To prevent the simulation of hardware with user-controlled software, a so-called "hardware root of trust" is used.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] This is a set of private keys that are embedded directly into the chip during manufacturing; one-time programmable memory such as eFuses is usually used on mobile devices.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The hardware is designed in a way that prevents all software not signed by the trusted party's key from accessing the privileged features.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The public key of the vendor is provided at runtime and hashed; this hash is then compared to the one embedded in the chip.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] If the hash matches, the public key is used to verify a digital signature of trusted vendor-controlled firmware (such as a chain of bootloaders on Android devices or 'architectural enclaves' in SGX).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The trusted firmware is then used to implement remote attestation.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] When an application is attested, its untrusted components loads its trusted component into memory; the trusted application is protected from modification by untrusted components with hardware.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] A nonce is requested by the untrusted party from the verifier's server and is used as part of a cryptographic authentication protocol, proving integrity of the trusted application.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The proof is passed to the verifier, which verifies it.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] A valid proof cannot be computed in simulated hardware (i.e.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] QEMU) because in order to construct it, access to the keys baked into hardware is required; only trusted firmware has access to these keys and/or the keys derived from them or obtained using them.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Because only the platform owner is meant to have access to the data recorded in the foundry, the verifying party must interact with the service set up by the vendor.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] If the scheme is implemented improperly, the chip vendor can track which applications are used on which chip and selectively deny service by returning a message indicating that authentication has not passed.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] To simulate hardware in a way that enables it to pass remote authentication, an attacker would have to extract keys from the hardware, which is costly because of the equipment and technical skill required to execute it.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] For example, using focused ion beams, scanning electron microscopes, microprobing, and chip decapsulation is difficult, or even impossible, if the hardware is designed in such a way that reverse-engineering destroys the keys.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] In most cases, the keys are unique for each piece of hardware, so that a key extracted from one chip cannot be used by others (for example physically unclonable functions).
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Note: Much TEE literature covers this topic under the definition "premium content protection," which is the preferred nomenclature of many copyright holders.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Premium content protection is a specific use case of digital rights management (DRM) and is controversial among some communities, such as the Free Software Foundation.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] It is widely used by copyright holders to restrict the ways in which end users can consume content such as 4K high-definition films.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is a suitable environment for protecting digitally encoded information (for example, HD films or audio) on connected devices such as smartphones, tablets, and HD televisions.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] This suitability comes from the ability of the TEE to deprive the owner of the device of access stored secrets, and the fact that there is often a protected hardware path between the TEE and the display and/or subsystems on devices.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is used to protect the content once it is on the device.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] While the content is protected during transmission or streaming by the use of encryption, the TEE protects the content once it has been decrypted on the device by ensuring that decrypted content is not exposed to the environment not approved by the app developer or platform vendor.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Mobile commerce applications such as: mobile wallets, peer-to-peer payments, contactless payments or using a mobile device as a point of sale (POS) terminal often have well-defined security requirements.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] In some scenarios, interaction with the end user is required, and this may require the user to expose sensitive information such as a PIN, password, or biometric identifier to the mobile OS as a means of authenticating the user.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE optionally offers a trusted user interface which can be used to construct user authentication on a mobile device.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of cryptocurrency, TEEs are increasingly used to implement crypto-wallets, as they offer the ability to store tokens more securely than regular operating systems, and can provide the necessary computation and authentication applications.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE is well-suited for supporting biometric identification methods (facial recognition, fingerprint sensor, and voice authorization), which may be easier to use and harder to steal than PINs and passwords.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] A TEE is a good area within a mobile device to house the matching engine and the associated processing required to authenticate the user.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The environment is designed to protect the data and establish a buffer against the non-secure apps located in mobile OSes.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] This additional security may help to satisfy the security needs of service providers in addition to keeping the costs low for handset developers.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE can be used by governments, enterprises, and cloud service providers to enable the secure handling of confidential information on mobile devices and on server infrastructure.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] The TEE offers a level of protection against software attacks generated in the mobile OS and assists in the control of access rights.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] It achieves this by housing sensitive, ‘trusted’ applications that need to be isolated and protected from the mobile OS and any malicious malware that may be present.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Through utilizing the functionality and security levels offered by the TEE, governments, and enterprises can be assured that employees using their own devices are doing so in a secure and trusted manner.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] Likewise, server-based TEEs help defend against internal and external attacks against backend infrastructure.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] With the rise of software assets and reuses, modular programming is the most productive process to design software architecture, by decoupling the functionalities into small independent modules.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] As each module contains everything necessary to execute its desired functionality, the TEE allows the organization of the complete system featuring a high level of reliability and security, while preventing each module from vulnerabilities of the others.
[src:secure-enclave-usage/trusted-execution-environment] In order for the modules to communicate and share data, TEE provides means to securely have payloads sent/received between the modules, using mechanisms such as object serialization, in conjunction with proxies.
